by ruudk at 2024-08-10T18:19:45Z

I ran the bench on my machine:

```
// v3 branch
Benchmark 1: php bench.php
  Time (mean Â± Ïƒ):     110.2 ms Â±   3.7 ms    [User: 98.5 ms, System: 7.4 ms]
  Range (min â€¦ max):   108.6 ms â€¦ 126.9 ms    23 runs

// this branch
Benchmark 1: php bench.php
  Time (mean Â± Ïƒ):      1.018 s Â±  0.010 s    [User: 0.991 s, System: 0.009 s]
  Range (min â€¦ max):    1.007 s â€¦  1.032 s    10 runs
```

When I change the `stripcslashes` method:
```diff
 private function stripcslashes(string $str, string $quoteType): string
 {
+    if (!str_contains($str, '\\')) {
+        return $str;
+    }
+    // ...
```

it becomes this:
```
// this branch
Benchmark 1: php bench.php
  Time (mean Â± Ïƒ):      95.7 ms Â±   1.1 ms    [User: 84.9 ms, System: 7.5 ms]
  Range (min â€¦ max):    94.5 ms â€¦  99.0 ms    29 runs
```

But obviously, that's because the bench does not contain any escape characters.

So let's change the bench to:
```php
<?php

require_once __DIR__.'/vendor/autoload.php';

$string = str_repeat("æ—¥æœ¬ã§ã¯ã€æ˜¥ã«ãªã‚‹ã¨æ¡œã®èŠ±ãŒå’²ãã¾ã™ã€‚\nå¤šãã®äººã€…ã¯ã€å…¬åœ’ã‚„å·ã®è¿‘ãã«é›†ã¾ã‚Šã€ãŠèŠ±è¦‹ã‚’æ¥½ã—ã¿ã¾ã™ã€‚\\næ¡œã®èŠ±ã³ã‚‰ãŒé¢¨ã«èˆžã„ã€ã¾ã‚‹ã§é›ªã®ã‚ˆã†ã«è¦‹ãˆã‚‹çž¬é–“ã¯ã€ã¨ã¦ã‚‚ç¾Žã—ã„ã§ã™ã€‚", 10);
$loader = new Twig\Loader\ArrayLoader([
    'index.twig' => <<<EOF
{{ "$string" }}
EOF
    ,
]);

$twig = new Twig\Environment($loader);

for ($i = 0; $i < 10000; $i++) {
    $twig->tokenize(new Twig\Source($twig->getLoader()->getSourceContext('index.twig')->getCode(), 'index.twig'));
}
```

Now we get
```
// this branch
Benchmark 1: php bench.php
  Time (mean Â± Ïƒ):      1.026 s Â±  0.002 s    [User: 0.999 s, System: 0.008 s]
  Range (min â€¦ max):    1.024 s â€¦  1.029 s    10 runs
```

So the `str_contains` check is making it a bit slower when there is a backslash found. But when there is not, it can return the raw string directly, making it even faster than v3.

